This paper is primarily focused on face recognition, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) category. The paper also proposes a learning approach using a two-stream convolutional neural network, which involves training a complex model and distilling its knowledge to a simpler model, which falls under the machine learning (cs.LG) category. The paper also involves solving a sparse graph optimization problem, which falls under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) category. Additionally, the paper involves experiments with memory and speed performance, which falls under the multimedia (cs.MM) category. Finally, the paper also involves discussing potential security implications of low-resolution face recognition, which falls under the cryptography and security (cs.CR) category.
